C# 9.0 enables extension `GetEnumerator` support for `foreach` loops:

[What's new in C# 9.0] (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/whats-new/csharp-9)

If there is no instance `GetEnumerator` method and there is more than one reachable `GetEnumerator` extension method, the C# compiler correctly chooses the closest one. For instance:

```c#
using System.Collections;
using Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting;
using UnitTestProject1;

namespace UnitTestProject1
{
    [TestClass]
    public class UnitTest1
    {
        [TestMethod]
        public void TestMethod1()
        {
            var c = new C();
            foreach (var i in c) ;
        }
    }

public class C { }

public static class Extensions
    {
        public static IEnumerator GetEnumerator(this C c) => new int[0]. GetEnumerator(); // The compiler chooses this extension method.
    }
}

public static class Extensions
{
    public static IEnumerator GetEnumerator(this C c) => new int[0]. GetEnumerator();
}
```

The previous example compiles and runs just fine. However, IntelliSense incorrectly flags the usage of variable `c` in the `foreach` loop, stating:

`Type 'UnitTestProject.C' cannot be used in 'foreach' statement because it neither implements 'IEnumerable' or 'IEnumerable<T>', nor has suitable 'GetEnumerator' method which return type has 'Current' property and 'MoveNext' method`

Removing either of the extension methods causes the flag to go away.

